Date: 1/12/1865
Source: Station Life in NZ
Author: BARKER
Vol / Page: 33
Edition: 1874
Quote: We next inspected the wool tables, to which two boys were incessantly bringing armfuls of rolled-up fleeces; these were laid out on the tables before the wool-sorters, who opened them out, and pronounced in a moment to which <i>bin</i> they belonged ....<i>Ibid.</i> I was most impressed by the silence in the shed; not a sound was to be heard except the click of the shears, and the wool-sorter's decision as he flings the fleece behind him, given in one, or at most two words.
